<div id="review_3527500872" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3527500872" />
    <a title="Jo" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/12091097-jo"><img alt="Jo" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1346006680p2/12091097.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3527500872?book_show_action=true">Sep 12, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jo" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jo" href="/user/show/12091097-jo">Jo</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780486796963" href="/book/show/25490497-pericles">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3527500872" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2188944521796326099">Sometimes the reason a Shakespeare play isn’t as well known is obvious once you’ve read it and Pericles is one of those. The first half is confusing as Pericles moves around from state to state in a kind of Odyssey and the language doesn’t help. Characters are introduced for a few scenes and then disappear which doesn’t help with the cohesiveness of the play. <br/><br/>Once he meets Thaisa it seems to flow far better and is easier to read and funnily enough after I’d finished my read I found out that Shak</span>
  <span id="freeText2188944521796326099" style="display:none">Sometimes the reason a Shakespeare play isn’t as well known is obvious once you’ve read it and Pericles is one of those. The first half is confusing as Pericles moves around from state to state in a kind of Odyssey and the language doesn’t help. Characters are introduced for a few scenes and then disappear which doesn’t help with the cohesiveness of the play. <br /><br />Once he meets Thaisa it seems to flow far better and is easier to read and funnily enough after I’d finished my read I found out that Shakespeare is believed to have written this as a collaboration and he is largely responsible for the second half. The plot line is very Shakespearean in the sense of missing family members, those who were thought dead are alive, villainous plots etc but as a whole it just doesn’t succeed as well as some of his other more well known plays. Having said that, I know that rereading of the plays often helps me appreciate them more so perhaps a reread will be in my future.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2188944521796326099" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


