    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_547486138" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/547486138" />
    <a title="Ben" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/9592279-ben"><img alt="Ben" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1533140387p2/9592279.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/547486138?book_show_action=true">Feb 26, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ben" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ben" href="/user/show/9592279-ben">Ben</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer547486138" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9648195017045048637">Some suggest that this play was not written by Shakespeare at all, while others believe that Shakespeare wrote at least part of this work (much of it likely written by George Wilkins). Authenticity aside, this play does not contain the best verse in the Shakespearean canon. In fact, it seems rather strained at times. But what saves the work is not the writing, but the plot. This is a touching and tender romance, with bits of comedy (I find the dialogue in the two reunion scenes in Act V -- betwe</span>
  <span id="freeText9648195017045048637" style="display:none">Some suggest that this play was not written by Shakespeare at all, while others believe that Shakespeare wrote at least part of this work (much of it likely written by George Wilkins). Authenticity aside, this play does not contain the best verse in the Shakespearean canon. In fact, it seems rather strained at times. But what saves the work is not the writing, but the plot. This is a touching and tender romance, with bits of comedy (I find the dialogue in the two reunion scenes in Act V -- between Pericles and his daughter Marina, and later his wife Thaisa -- that T.S. Eliot described as "ultra-dramatic" to be very comedic, though this may be a misreading on my part; seeing the play staged might influence my initial reading). Overall, it is a story about love and reunion, similar in nature to "The Winter's Tale," Shakespeare's better known and better written work. <br /><br />I decided to begin this year by tackling the entirety of Shakespeare's works -- the poetry and the 37 plays (the authenticity of "Pericles" is questionable but it has been longer accepted as part of the Shakespearean canon than "The Two Noble Kinsmen," which is the only "Shakespeare work" I've yet to read). This was my last of the plays -- now I just have the poetry. Aside from the verse, which is not horrible, but not the best either (by a long shot), it was an enjoyable work. </span>
  <a data-text-id="9648195017045048637" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


